1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,160
This question comes from me.

2
00:00:02,160 --> 00:00:04,480
It's a new chapter from the 10th anniversary edition of What If,

3
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:06,000
which is now available online and in print.

4
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:07,990
At the end of the laser pointer video,

5
00:00:07,990 --> 00:00:11,000
we constructed an array of lasers with a total power of 2x10^24 watts,

6
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:12,369
which not only lit up the moon,

7
00:00:12,369 --> 00:00:15,000
but violently ejected it from orbit around the Earth.

8
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:17,000
We decided that was enough power.

9
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:18,000
But why?

10
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:19,000
You can always make a number bigger.

11
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:20,000
No one can stop you.

12
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:22,000
There are infinitely many numbers.

13
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,000
And I want to know, what if we tried even more power?

14
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,000
A 2x10^24 watt laser is powerful.

15
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,030
When we turned ours on,

16
00:00:31,030 --> 00:00:35,000
it made the moon-facing surface of the Earth significantly more luminous than the sun.

17
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:37,000
That's impressive, but we can do better.

18
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:41,000
The universe contains death rays that make our moon-obliterating beam look like a handheld laser pointer.

19
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:47,000
A gamma ray is just what we call a very high-energy photon of electromagnetic radiation.

20
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:49,000
When you see a chart of the electromagnetic spectrum,

21
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:52,000
gamma rays are basically anything more energetic than X-rays.

22
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:54,000
At the high end, they're literally off the chart.

23
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
They come from high-energy events like nuclear explosions.

24
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Gamma-ray bursts are made when something very bad happens to a star.

25
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:01,079
When massive stars collapse,

26
00:01:01,079 --> 00:01:04,000
their cores give in to the crushing pull of their own gravity,

27
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:05,379
release an enormous burst of energy,

28
00:01:05,379 --> 00:01:07,000
and tear the star apart from the inside.

29
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
For reasons that we don't fully understand,

30
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:13,000
these explosions often produce jets shooting away along the poles of the collapsing star.

31
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:15,099
These jets can travel across much of the universe,

32
00:01:15,099 --> 00:01:17,000
and when Earth is in line with one of them,

33
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:19,000
we see it as a flash of gamma rays from deep space.

34
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:24,000
We didn't know about gamma-ray bursts until we launched a satellite to watch for gamma-ray flashes from nuclear explosions on Earth,

35
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,000
and we were surprised to see flashes coming from everywhere else in the universe instead.

36
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,000
The peak power of beams from gamma-ray bursts can be on the order of 10 to the 44 watts,

37
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
which is much, much more powerful than our laser array.

38
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
To get a 10 to the 44 watt death ray of our own,

39
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:42,000
we'd need to give each person on the moon-facing side of the planet a 2 times 10 to the 34 watt laser.

40
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:42,439
That is,

41
00:01:42,439 --> 00:01:48,000
each person would need a laser 10 billion times more powerful than the final combined laser that violently ejected the moon.

42
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,120
This is an implausible scenario,

43
00:01:50,120 --> 00:01:52,000
and it wouldn't work for reasons we'll get to in a minute.

44
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
But first, let's think about what we could do with a beam like that.

45
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:56,200
We'd have to focus it carefully,

46
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:58,000
since laser beams spread out as they travel.

47
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
The minimum angle of spread depends on the size of the source of the beam.

48
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,439
For laser beams emitted by lenses 2 meters wide, the limit is about 0.1

49
00:02:04,439 --> 00:02:07,000
arcseconds, or 3/100,000th of a degree.

50
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:13,000
The laser beam limit formula is weirdly similar to the formula used to determine the maximum resolution of telescopes like Hubble,

51
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,000
because, in a sense, a telescope is just a death ray running in reverse.

52
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:17,150
Hubble has a 2.4

53
00:02:17,150 --> 00:02:20,449
meter mirror, and its angular resolution is a little less than 0.1

54
00:02:20,449 --> 00:02:24,000
arcseconds, similar to the angular limit of our 2 meter laser.

55
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,590
The laser array from the original chapter was pretty powerful,

56
00:02:26,590 --> 00:02:28,000
but not particularly narrow.

57
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,050
If it had been focused into a Hubble-style beam,

58
00:02:30,050 --> 00:02:34,000
it could conceivably have fried the surfaces of planets anywhere in our galaxy.

59
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
A 10 to the 44 watt death ray would be much worse.

60
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,030
If we tightly focused it down to the diffraction limit,

61
00:02:39,030 --> 00:02:41,000
it could reach targets far outside our galaxy,

62
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,000
frying the surfaces of planets up to 5 or 10 billion light years away.

63
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
But don't rush out to buy a 10 to the 44 watt laser just yet.

64
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
At cosmic energy scales, normal optics breaks down.

65
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:53,310
For example, if a beam is powerful enough,

66
00:02:53,310 --> 00:02:56,000
it could exert a gravitational pull on itself.

67
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Photons carry energy, and energy creates gravitational fields.

68
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,000
For normal light beams, this is negligible.

69
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
But for a 10 to the 44 watt laser the size of the Earth,

70
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
photons on the outer edge would experience an acceleration of over 10 G's toward the beam's center line.

71
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
But physics has another surprise,

72
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
one that finally puts an upper limit on how powerful lasers can get.

73
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,069
Namely, if a beam of light gets too bright,

74
00:03:16,069 --> 00:03:18,000
space itself stops being transparent.

75
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:21,000
If you pack enough laser energy into a small enough space,

76
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:26,000
quantum mechanics predicts that the strong electromagnetic fields will result in spontaneous creation of particles and antiparticles.

77
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,000
These particles, mostly electrons and positrons,

78
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:30,000
would intercept some of the laser energy,

79
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,000
which would result in more particles being created.

80
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,000
For laser power densities above about 10 to the 26 watts per square centimeter,

81
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
this process is expected to cascade,

82
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:43,000
fully halting the laser's progress and providing an upper limit on how much power our beam can have.

83
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
In the end, it turns out, physics is not math.

84
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,099
You can always find a bigger number,

85
00:03:48,099 --> 00:03:50,000
but you can't always make a bigger laser.

